      <section id=3D"roles">
        <!-- review? -->
        <h3><span>4.3 </span>Schema Roles</h3>
        <!--
          XXX needs rewrite, Dave doesn=E2=80=99t understand, ergo no one w=
ill
          DC suggests contrasting two examples: one in which I am eternally=
 indentured to the
          Illuminati, versus one in which I am just a hired gun.
        -->
        <p>
          It is worth taking a step back to understand the importance of th=
e <em>role</em>
          modeling. Its application is clearly exemplified in the <a href=
=3D"https://w3c.github.io/scholarly-html/#authors">Authors &amp;
          Contributors</a> section wherein a <a href=3D"http://ns.science.a=
i/#ContributorRole" class=3D"onto">sa:ContributorRole</a> type is used as a=
 wrapper
          and not <a href=3D"http://schema.org/Person" class=3D"onto">schem=
a:Person</a> or <a href=3D"http://schema.org/Organization" class=3D"onto">s=
chema:Organization</a> directly.
        </p>
        <p>
          Roles are an indirection that provides additional information abo=
ut a property or
          relationship. A simple overview is provided in the schema.org blo=
g post
          <a href=3D"http://blog.schema.org/2014/06/introducing-role.html">=
Introducing =E2=80=99Role=E2=80=99</a>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Let=E2=80=99s look at the example of authorship information. Some=
 properties of the agent who
          authored the document (person or organization), such as their nam=
e, are considered to be
          true outside the limited context of the document. These propertie=
s will be set directly on
          the agent.
        </p>
        <p>
          On the other hand, other properties are considered to be specific=
 to the agent
          <em>in their role as author of the document</em>. To give an exam=
ple, were I to be
          writing the document you are currently reading as a freelancer fo=
r the Illuminati, my
          affiliation to them would be solely in my role as author and I sh=
ould not be considered
          eternally indentured to them.
        </p>
        <p>
          When a role is used to enrich a property, the convention is to ha=
ve it as the value of
          that property, and then to repeat the property on the role to poi=
nt to the object. At
          first glance it sounds contrived, but it is a simple and powerful=
 construct. To stay with
          the authoring example, the indirection would look like:
        </p>
        <p>
          <a href=3D"http://schema.org/ScholarlyArticle" class=3D"onto">sch=
ema:ScholarlyArticle</a> =E2=9F=BC
          <em><a href=3D"http://schema.org/author" class=3D"onto">schema:au=
thor</a></em> =E2=9F=BC
          <a href=3D"http://ns.science.ai/#ContributorRole" class=3D"onto">=
sa:ContributorRole</a> =E2=9F=BC
          <em><a href=3D"http://schema.org/author" class=3D"onto">schema:au=
thor</a></em> =E2=9F=BC
          <a href=3D"http://schema.org/Person" class=3D"onto">schema:Person=
</a>
        </p>
        <p>
          To demonstrate how properties can attach differently to the role =
and to the agent, we can
          unfold the authorship example further:
        </p>
        <figure typeof=3D"schema:SoftwareSourceCode" resource=3D"#role-exam=
ple" id=3D"role-example">
          <pre><a href=3D"http://schema.org/ScholarlyArticle" class=3D"onto=
">schema:ScholarlyArticle</a>
=E2=94=94=E2=94=80<a href=3D"http://schema.org/author" class=3D"onto">schem=
a:author</a>
  =E2=94=94=E2=94=80<a href=3D"http://ns.science.ai/#ContributorRole" class=
=3D"onto">sa:ContributorRole</a>
    =E2=94=9C=E2=94=80<a href=3D"http://schema.org/author" class=3D"onto">s=
chema:author</a>
    =E2=94=82 =E2=94=94=E2=94=80<a href=3D"http://schema.org/Person" class=
=3D"onto">schema:Person</a>
    =E2=94=82   =E2=94=9C=E2=94=80<a href=3D"http://schema.org/name" class=
=3D"onto">schema:name</a> =3D Bruce Banner
    =E2=94=82   =E2=94=94=E2=94=80<a href=3D"http://schema.org/url" class=
=3D"onto">schema:url</a> =3D http://berjon.com/
    =E2=94=94=E2=94=80<a href=3D"http://ns.science.ai/#roleAffiliation" cla=
ss=3D"onto">sa:roleAffiliation</a>
      =E2=94=94=E2=94=80<a href=3D"http://schema.org/Organization" class=3D=
"onto">schema:Organization</a>
        =E2=94=9C=E2=94=80<a href=3D"http://schema.org/name" class=3D"onto"=
>schema:name</a> =3D Illuminati
        =E2=94=94=E2=94=80<a href=3D"http://schema.org/address" class=3D"on=
to">schema:address</a> =3D Bavaria
          </pre>
          <figcaption>
            <span property=3D"schema:name"></span>
            <span property=3D"schema:description">
              Example of a role being used to model authorship. This effect=
ively states that my
              affiliation <em>as a contributor</em> is to the Illuminati an=
d that my name
              <em>as a person</em> is Bruce Banner.
