        </figure>
      </section>
      <section id=3D"actions">
        <!-- review? -->
        <h3><span>4.4 </span>Actions</h3>
        <p>
          Actions are a global <a role=3D"doc-biblioref" href=3D"https://w3=
c.github.io/scholarly-html/#ref-schema.org">schema.org</a> mechanism to con=
vey facts
          about things that can be or have been <em>done</em>. There is an
          <a href=3D"http://schema.org/docs/actions.html">overview document=
 for actions</a> but it
          dives deep very fast and may be more confusing than helpful. This=
 sections intends to
          convey all that one needs to know about actions in order to under=
stand their usage in
          Scholarly HTML (keeping in mind that they can do much more).
        </p>
        <p>
          Note that actions can do much more than what Scholarly HTML uses =
them for. For instance,
          if you use an email client that supports actions (such as GMail) =
you may have noticed that
          some emails allow for direct interactions: those are implemented =
using actions, and
          without scripting.
        </p>
        <p>
          Actions have a type (e.g. <code>ReadAction</code>, <code>DrinkAct=
ion</code>), a status
          (completed, in progress=E2=80=A6), an agent being whoever carries=
 it out, and an object which is
          what they are being done to. They can also have start and end tim=
es (as well as several
          other properties which we won=E2=80=99t go into here). Scholarly =
articles typically feature
          indications about things that people have done, which is a good f=
it for modeling with
          actions. A few examples should help clarify the notion.
        </p>
        <p>
          When referencing an online work, it is customary to indicate the =
access date for it (since
          it may have changed in the meantime). This can be modeled as a <a=
 href=3D"http://schema.org/ReadAction" class=3D"onto">schema:ReadAction</a>=
,
          with its <a href=3D"http://schema.org/actionStatus" class=3D"onto=
">schema:actionStatus</a> set to <code>CompletedActionStatus</code>, and a
          <a href=3D"http://schema.org/endTime" class=3D"onto">schema:endTi=
me</a> being the access date. In JSON-LD it would look like this:
        </p>
        <figure typeof=3D"schema:SoftwareSourceCode" resource=3D"#read-acti=
on-example" id=3D"read-action-example">
          <pre><code>
{
  "@type":        "ReadAction",
  "actionStatus": "CompletedActionStatus",
  "endTime":      "1977-03-15"
}
          </code></pre>
          <figcaption>
            <span property=3D"schema:name"></span>
            <span property=3D"schema:description">
              Example of a <a href=3D"http://schema.org/ReadAction" class=
=3D"onto">schema:ReadAction</a> used to model the access date of an online
              citation. Both the object and the agent are implicit in the c=
ontext in which it is
              used.
            </span>
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>
          Authors often acknowledge the contributions of others or have to =
disclose potential
          conflicts of interest that may stem from their interactions outsi=
de of the article.
          The former can be conveyed as an <a href=3D"http://ns.science.ai/=
#AcknowledgeAction" class=3D"onto">sa:AcknowledgeAction</a> in which the
          <a href=3D"http://schema.org/name" class=3D"onto">schema:name</a>=
 of the action is the verb part of the acknowledgement and the
          <a href=3D"http://schema.org/recipient" class=3D"onto">schema:rec=
ipient</a> is the person (or entity of any kind) being acknowledged. The
          agent is typically implicitly specified as the object to which th=
e action is attached.
        </p>
        <figure typeof=3D"schema:SoftwareSourceCode" resource=3D"#read-acti=
on-example" id=3D"read-action-example">
          <pre><code>
{
  "@type": "AcknowledgeAction",
  "actionStatus": "CompletedActionStatus",
  "name": "is thankful for the pioneering contribution of",
  "recipient": {
    "@type": "Person",
    "name": "Vannevar Bush",
  }
}
            </code></pre>
