            <span property=3D"schema:name"></span>
            <span property=3D"schema:description">
              Example of an <a href=3D"http://ns.science.ai/#AcknowledgeAct=
ion" class=3D"onto">sa:AcknowledgeAction</a> in which the author (not shown=
) acknowledges
              contributions from Vannevar Bush.
            </span>
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
      </section>
      <section id=3D"article-title-semantics">
        <!-- review? -->
        <h3><span>4.5 </span>Article and Title Semantics</h3>
        <p>
          The <code>article</code> element that roots the content of the Sc=
holarly HTML document
          needs further refinement to capture the specific type of article =
that it encodes. The
          <code>typeof</code> attribute should always contain <a href=3D"ht=
tp://schema.org/ScholarlyArticle" class=3D"onto">schema:ScholarlyArticle</a=
> as its
          first item, but it can be further refined with additional article=
 types.
        </p>
        <p class=3D"issue">
          Should we recommend a specific taxonomy for article (sub)typing? =
There are so many:
          Fabio, MeSH, NPG=E2=80=A6
        </p>
        <p>
          In order for arbitrary parts of the document to be able to attach=
 metadata to the
          <code>article</code>, it also needs to have its <code>resource</c=
ode> attribute set to a
          URL that can be referenced (it is typically sufficient to just us=
e <code>#</code> for that
          purpose).
        </p>
        <p>
          While the <code>h1</code> in the document=E2=80=99s <code>header<=
/code> is sufficient to convey
          the fact that it is the document=E2=80=99s title, some services u=
se extraneous information in
          order to assign an unambiguous title to the document. As such, it=
 needs to have its
          <code>property</code> attribute set to <a href=3D"http://schema.o=
rg/name" class=3D"onto">schema:name</a>. Similary, if a subtitle is
          present in the <code>header</code> it needs to be decorated with =
both a <code>role</code>
          of <code>doc-subtitle</code> (to expose its <a role=3D"doc-biblio=
ref" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/scholarly-html/#ref-DPUB-ARIA">DPUB-ARIA=
</a>
          semantics) and a <code>property</code> of <a href=3D"http://schem=
a.org/alternateName" class=3D"onto">schema:alternateName</a>.
        </p>
        <p>
          If appropriate, the beginning of the <code>article</code> is also=
 a good place in which to
          capture the accessibility properties of the document, using the r=
elevant parts of
          <a role=3D"doc-biblioref" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/scholarly=
-html/#ref-schema.org">schema.org</a> (<a href=3D"http://schema.org/accessi=
bilityFeature" class=3D"onto">schema:accessibilityFeature</a>,
          <a href=3D"http://schema.org/accessibilityHazard" class=3D"onto">=
schema:accessibilityHazard</a>, <a href=3D"http://schema.org/accessibilityA=
PI" class=3D"onto">schema:accessibilityAPI</a>, and
          <a href=3D"http://schema.org/accessibilityControl" class=3D"onto"=
>schema:accessibilityControl</a>, as detailed in
          <a href=3D"https://www.w3.org/wiki/WebSchemas/Accessibility">the =
WebSchemas Accessibility
          wiki page</a>).
        </p>
        <figure typeof=3D"schema:SoftwareSourceCode" resource=3D"#article-e=
xample" id=3D"article-example">
          <pre><code>
&lt;article <strong>resource=3D"#" typeof=3D"schema:ScholarlyArticle"</stro=
ng>&gt;
  &lt;header&gt;
    &lt;h1 <strong>property=3D"schema:name"</strong>&gt;Is Cryptopaleozoolo=
gy Hopeless?&lt;/h1&gt;
    &lt;p <strong>role=3D"doc-subtitle" property=3D"schema:alternateName"</=
strong>&gt;
      The Future of the Scientific Method
    &lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/header&gt;
  <strong>&lt;meta property=3D"schema:accessibilityFeature" content=3D"alte=
rnativeText"&gt;
  &lt;meta property=3D"schema:accessibilityFeature" content=3D"MathML"&gt;
  &lt;meta property=3D"schema:accessibilityHazard" content=3D"noFlashingHaz=
ard"&gt;</strong>
&lt;/article&gt;
          </code></pre>
          <figcaption>
            <span property=3D"schema:name"></span>
            <span property=3D"schema:description">
              Example of <code>article</code> and title markup.
            </span>
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
      </section>
      <section id=3D"contentinfo-semantics">
        <!-- review? -->
        <h3><span>4.6 </span>The <code>contentinfo</code> Region Semantics<=
/h3>
        <p>
          As described in the <a href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/scholarly-ht=
ml/#structure">Structure section</a>, the <code>contentinfo</code>
          region serves as a container for the metadata of the article. It =
is itself nothing more
          than a <code>div</code> with a <code>role</code> of <code>content=
info</code>, but its
          content has rich structure.
        </p>
        <p>
          It contains a list of <code>section</code> elements, each of whic=
h is identified with a
          specific <code>typeof</code> attribute.
        </p>
        <section id=3D"authors">
          <!-- review? -->
          <h4><span>4.6.1 </span>Authors &amp; Contributors</h4>
          <p>
            If the document has authors or contributors, they are listed in=
 a <code>section</code>
            with <code>typeof</code> <a href=3D"http://ns.science.ai/#Autho=
rsList" class=3D"onto">sa:AuthorsList</a>. The content of that <code>sectio=
n</code>
            is an <code>h2</code> title appropriate for it, followed by eit=
her a <code>ul</code> or
            <code>ol</code> (depending on whether the authors are considere=
d ordered, which is
            highly dependent on the discipline=E2=80=99s culture).
          </p>
          <p>
            Each <code>li</code> in that list must feature a <code>typeof</=
code> of
            <a href=3D"http://ns.science.ai/#ContributorRole" class=3D"onto=
">sa:ContributorRole</a> and a property of either <a href=3D"http://schema.=
org/author" class=3D"onto">schema:author</a> or
            <a href=3D"http://schema.org/contributor" class=3D"onto">schema=
:contributor</a> depending on which is applicable. Modeling with schema.org
            roles is explained in the <a href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/scho=
larly-html/#roles">Roles</a> section.
          </p>
          <p>
            The <a href=3D"http://ns.science.ai/#ContributorRole" class=3D"=
onto">sa:ContributorRole</a> <code>span</code> is structured as follows:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              Exactly one <code>span</code> with a <code>property</code> of=
 either
              <a href=3D"http://schema.org/author" class=3D"onto">schema:au=
thor</a> or <a href=3D"http://schema.org/contributor" class=3D"onto">schema=
:contributor</a> (matching the one that points to the
              role) and <code>typeof</code> either <a href=3D"http://schema=
.org/Person" class=3D"onto">schema:Person</a> (if the author is a sentient
              entity) or <a href=3D"http://schema.org/Organization" class=
=3D"onto">schema:Organization</a> (if it is a collective thereof). How to c=
apture
              persons and organizations is detailed in the creatively-named
              <a href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/scholarly-html/#person-org">=
Persons &amp; Organizations</a> section.
            </li>
            <li>
              Zero or more <code>a</code> elements with a <code>property</c=
ode> of
              <a href=3D"http://ns.science.ai/#roleAffiliation" class=3D"on=
to">sa:roleAffiliation</a>, one for each affiliation of the author in produ=
cing the
              article. Each of those elements needs further to have a <code=
>resource</code>
              attribute matching the one on the affiliation it is pointing =
to and an
              <code>href</code> attribute linking to the element on which t=
hat affiliation is
              defined. The <code>a</code> element may contain arbitrary tex=
t (typically a number,
              letter, or symbol matching that used by the target in its own=
 list). These should not
              occur if the agent is an organization.
            </li>
            <li>
              Zero or more <code>a</code> elements with a <code>property</c=
ode> of
              <a href=3D"http://ns.science.ai/#roleAction" class=3D"onto">s=
a:roleAction</a>, one for each comment describing the author=E2=80=99s spec=
ific
              contribution to the work (e.g. "Authors contributed equally" =
or "Designed the study").
              Each of those elements needs further to have a <code>resource=
</code>
              attribute matching the one on the note it is pointing to and =
an
              <code>href</code> attribute linking to the element which cont=
ains that note. The
              <code>a</code> element may contain arbitrary text (typically =
a number, letter, or
              symbol matching that used by the target in its own list).
            </li>
            <li>
              Zero or one <code>ul</code> elements. Each of its <code>li</c=
ode> children has a
              <code>property</code> of <a href=3D"http://schema.org/roleCon=
tactPoint" class=3D"onto">schema:roleContactPoint</a> and a <code>typeof</c=
ode> set
              to <a href=3D"http://schema.org/ContactPoint" class=3D"onto">=
schema:ContactPoint</a>. The content of each <code>li</code> can be anythin=
g
              that describes a manner of contacting the author in question,=
 but it will typically
              involve properties such as <a href=3D"http://schema.org/email=
" class=3D"onto">schema:email</a>, <a href=3D"http://schema.org/telephone" =
class=3D"onto">schema:telephone</a>,
              <a href=3D"http://schema.org/address" class=3D"onto">schema:a=
ddress</a>, <a href=3D"http://schema.org/description" class=3D"onto">schema=
:description</a> (for arbitrary descriptions of the
              contact method), or for journals publishing to the Web of the=
 early 1980s
              <a href=3D"http://schema.org/faxNumber" class=3D"onto">schema=
:faxNumber</a>.
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Here is an example of a complete kitchen sink authors=E2=80=99 =
section. Note that in most cases
            the markup will be much simpler =E2=80=94 this exercises far mo=
re of the features than there
            is information for in a typical case.
          </p>
          <figure typeof=3D"schema:SoftwareSourceCode" resource=3D"#authors=
-example" id=3D"authors-example">
            <pre><code>
&lt;section typeof=3D"sa:AuthorsList"&gt;
  &lt;h2&gt;Authors&lt;/h2&gt;
  &lt;ul&gt;
    &lt;li typeof=3D"sa:ContributorRole" property=3D"schema:author"&gt;
      &lt;span typeof=3D"schema:Person"
            resource=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Henry_Holland"&g=
t;
        &lt;meta property=3D"schema:givenName" content=3D"John"&gt;
        &lt;meta property=3D"schema:additionalName" content=3D"Henry"&gt;
        &lt;meta property=3D"schema:familyName" content=3D"Holland"&gt;
        &lt;span property=3D"schema:name"&gt;John H. Holland&lt;/span&gt;
      &lt;/span&gt;
      &lt;a href=3D"#sf" property=3D"sa:roleAffiliation" resource=3D"http:/=
/www.santafe.edu/"&gt;a&lt;/a&gt;,
      &lt;a href=3D"#umich" property=3D"sa:roleAffiliation" resource=3D"htt=
p://umich.edu/"&gt;b&lt;/a&gt;,
      &lt;a href=3D"#note1" property=3D"sa:roleAction" resource=3D"#note1" =
rel=3D"footnote"&gt;1&lt;/a&gt;
      &lt;ul&gt;
        &lt;li property=3D"schema:roleContactPoint" typeof=3D"schema:Contac=
tPoint"&gt;
          &lt;a href=3D"mailto:jholland@umich.edu"
             property=3D"schema:email"&gt;jholland@umich.edu&lt;/a&gt;
        &lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li property=3D"schema:roleContactPoint" typeof=3D"schema:Contac=
tPoint"&gt;
          &lt;a href=3D"fax:+4815162342" property=3D"schema:faxNumber"&gt;+=
4815162342&lt;/a&gt;
        &lt;/li&gt;
      &lt;/ul&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
            </code></pre>
            <figcaption>
              <span property=3D"schema:name"></span>
              <span property=3D"schema:description">
                Example of an author (<code>schema:contributor</code> could=
 also have been used).
                The links to <code>#sf</code>, <code>#umich</code>, and <co=
de>#note1</code> are
                expected to point to items in the <a href=3D"https://w3c.gi=
thub.io/scholarly-html/#affiliations">Affiliations</a> section
                for the first two, and in the <a href=3D"https://w3c.github=
.io/scholarly-html/#meta-notes">Notes</a> section for the
                last one.
              </span>
            </figcaption>
          </figure>
        </section>
        <section id=3D"affiliations">
          <!-- review? -->
          <h4><span>4.6.2 </span>Affiliations</h4>
          <p>
            If the authors and contributors of the documents are affiliated=
 with organizations, they
            are listed in a <code>section</code> with <code>typeof</code> <=
a href=3D"http://ns.science.ai/#Affiliations" class=3D"onto">sa:Affiliation=
s</a>.
            The content of that <code>section</code> is an <code>h2</code> =
title appropriate for it,
            followed by a <code>ul</code> or <code>ol</code> (but the order=
 is less commonly
            relevant than it is for authors).
          </p>
          <p>
            Note that articles that feature an organization as an author sh=
ould have that
            organization listed in the <a href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/sch=
olarly-html/#authors">Authors &amp; Contributors</a> section,
            and <em>not</em> here.
          </p>
          <p>
            Each <code>li</code> in the list is one affiliation (though mul=
tiple people can
            reference it). The <code>li</code> needs to have an <code>id</c=
ode> matching that used
            in the reference. Inside the <code>li</code> is a <code>span</c=
ode> with
            <code>typeof</code> set to <a href=3D"http://schema.org/Organiz=
ation" class=3D"onto">schema:Organization</a> and its <code>resource</code>
            also matching the one used in the reference. (The belt and susp=
enders approach is
            unfortunately needed to produce both usable HTML and a viable d=
ata model.)
          </p>
          <p>
            The content of the <a href=3D"http://schema.org/Organization" c=
lass=3D"onto">schema:Organization</a> can contain any applicable property. =
An
            example of an affiliations section, with some extra structure f=
or the organization is
            given below.
          </p>
          <figure typeof=3D"schema:SoftwareSourceCode" resource=3D"#affilia=
tions-example" id=3D"affiliations-example">
            <pre><code>
&lt;section typeof=3D"sa:Affiliations"&gt;
  &lt;h2&gt;Affiliations&lt;/h2&gt;
  &lt;ul&gt;
    &lt;li id=3D"sa"&gt;
      &lt;span typeof=3D"schema:Organization" resource=3D"https://science.a=
i/"&gt;
        &lt;span property=3D"schema:name"&gt;science.ai&lt;/span&gt;,
        &lt;span property=3D"schema:parentOrganization"&gt;
          &lt;span typeof=3D"schema:Organization"&gt;
            &lt;span property=3D"schema:name"&gt;Standard Analytics&lt;/spa=
n&gt;
            =E2=80=94
            &lt;span property=3D"schema:location" typeof=3D"schema:Place"&g=
t;
              &lt;span property=3D"schema:address" typeof=3D"schema:PostalA=
ddress"&gt;
                &lt;span property=3D"schema:addressLocality"&gt;NYC&lt;/spa=
n&gt;,
                &lt;span property=3D"schema:addressRegion"&gt;NY&lt;/span&g=
t;,
                &lt;span property=3D"schema:addressCountry"&gt;USA&lt;/span=
&gt;
              &lt;/span&gt;
            &lt;/span&gt;
          &lt;/span&gt;
        &lt;/span&gt;
      &lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
            </code></pre>
            <figcaption>
              <span property=3D"schema:name"></span>
              <span property=3D"schema:description">
                Example of an organization section.
              </span>
            </figcaption>
          </figure>
        </section>
        <section id=3D"abstract-etc">
          <!-- review? -->
          <h4><span>4.6.3 </span>License, Copyright, Keywords, and Abstract=
</h4>
          <p>
            The copyright line of the document can be included in any eleme=
nt, but it must list two
            properties. <a href=3D"http://schema.org/copyrightYear" class=
=3D"onto">schema:copyrightYear</a> has a numeric value, and
            <a href=3D"http://schema.org/copyrightHolder" class=3D"onto">sc=
hema:copyrightHolder</a> has a value of <a href=3D"http://schema.org/Person=
" class=3D"onto">schema:Person</a> or
            <a href=3D"http://schema.org/Organization" class=3D"onto">schem=
a:Organization</a>.
          </p>
          <p>
            A link to the license for the article should be provided. The l=
ink should have the
            property of <a href=3D"http://schema.org/license" class=3D"onto=
">schema:license</a> and <code>typeof=3D"CreativeWork"</code>.
          </p>
          <!-- XXX insert simple license example to CC?-->
          <p>
            Keywords should be listed in a <code>section</code> element wit=
h an appropriate
            <code>h2</code>. The list of terms should be a <code>ul</code> =
with the
            <code>property</code> of <a href=3D"http://schema.org/keywords"=
 class=3D"onto">schema:keywords</a> on every <code>li</code>.
          </p>
          <p>
            The abstract should be included in a <code>section</code> eleme=
nt with
            <code>typeof</code> attribute containing <code>sa:Abstract</cod=
e>. The abstract should
            have the role of <code>doc-abstract</code>.
          </p>
        </section>
        <section id=3D"meta-notes">
          <!-- review? -->
          <h4><span>4.6.4 </span>Notes</h4>
          <p>
            Notes that add information about the <a href=3D"https://w3c.git=
hub.io/scholarly-html/#authors">Authors and Contributors</a>
            section should be hunk elements labeled as <code>doc-footnote</=
code>.
          </p>
          <!-- these are rdf:HTML? probably not -->
        </section>
      </section>
      <section id=3D"flavored-links">
        <!-- review? -->
        <h3><span>4.7 </span>Flavored Links</h3>
        <p>
          The <a href=3D"https://www.w3.org/TR/html51/semantics.html#linkTy=
pes"><code>rel</code></a>
          attribute should be applied to apply some spice to your links. Th=
e following values of
          <code>rel</code> should be used on the link that refers to these =
elements:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>footnote</li>
          <li>license</li>
          <li>stylesheet</li>
        </ul>
        <p class=3D"issue">
          There are many values for rel, such as glossary and bibliography =
that look like they are
          useful, but based on the definition, it sounds like they point to=
 the section containing
          the whole biblio. Not so helpful. rel=3D"citation" or "biblioentr=
y" would be more valuable.\
        </p>
      </section>
      <section id=3D"citations">
        <!-- review? -->
        <h3><span>4.8 </span>Citations &amp; References</h3>
        <p>
          Citations in scholarly articles provide a way to reference the wo=
rk of others upon which
          one builds. In the pre-Web era, they essentially served as links =
by carrying sufficient
          information for one to find the reference in question, in a relat=
ively compact manner.
        </p>
        <p>
          In a Web world, it can seem tempting to simply replace citations =
with links, but there is
          value in keeping the limited amount of metadata about the cited o=
bject that they provide
          inlined in the document. Links rot and disappear; when that happe=
ns the rest of the
          information can prove crucial in finding the referenced object at=
 some other location.
          Unique identifiers with indirect resolution, such as DOIs, might =
seem like a solution to
          this problem but being opaque humans routinely get them wrong. (D=
OIs additionally suffer
          from a single point of failure for resolution.) All things consid=
ered, including a link
          for convenience and human-readable metadata about the referenced =
object is likely the
          most resilient way to cite another document.
        </p>
        <p>
          In the print universe, reducing the number of pages one needs to =
use can be a noticeable
          cost-saver. Given that scholarly articles can easily feature doze=
ns if not hundreds of
          cited references, making use of compact reference conventions (as=
 well as smaller font
          sizes) made sense. Over time, however, what was a sensible idea d=
egenerated into a
          territorial maze of gratuitously heterogenous conventions to the =
point where there now
          exist <a href=3D"http://citationstyles.org/">over 8000 citation s=
tyles</a>.
        </p>
        <p>
          There is no value in Scholarly HTML so much as attempting to supp=
ort all citation styles.
          The Web does not need the compactness. Citations and references s=
hould be both data-rich
          and human-accessible, something on which the traditional formats =
fail, in some cases
          quite spectacularly.
        </p>
        <p>
          For accessibility purposes, Scholarly HTML recommends that refere=
nces be formatted in such
          a manner that they read naturally in the article=E2=80=99s natura=
l language, with articulations
          between the metadata parts, as below:
        </p>
        <figure typeof=3D"schema:SoftwareSourceCode" resource=3D"#citation-=
example" id=3D"citation-example">
          <pre><code>
&lt;li typeof=3D"schema:WebPage" role=3D"doc-biblioentry"
    resource=3D"http://semver.org/"
    property=3D"schema:citation" id=3D"some-id"&gt;
 &lt;cite property=3D"schema:name"&gt;
   &lt;a href=3D"http://semver.org/"&gt;Semantic Versioning 2.0.0&lt;/a&gt;
 &lt;/cite&gt;,
  by &lt;span property=3D"schema:author" typeof=3D"schema:Person"&gt;
   &lt;span property=3D"schema:givenName"&gt;Tom&lt;/span&gt;
   &lt;span property=3D"schema:familyName"&gt;Preston-Werner&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;/span&gt;; published in
 &lt;time property=3D"schema:datePublished" datatype=3D"xsd:gYear"
       datetime=3D"2014"&gt;2014&lt;/time&gt;
 &lt;span property=3D"schema:potentialAction" typeof=3D"schema:ReadAction"&=
gt;
   &lt;meta property=3D"schema:actionStatus" content=3D"CompletedActionStat=
us"&gt;
    (accessed on
   &lt;time property=3D"schema:endTime" datatype=3D"xsd:date"
         datetime=3D"2016-02-01"&gt;01 Feb 2016&lt;/time&gt;)
 &lt;/span&gt;.
&lt;/li&gt;
          </code></pre>
          <p>
            The above code renders as:
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li typeof=3D"schema:WebPage" role=3D"doc-biblioentry" resource=
=3D"http://semver.org/" property=3D"schema:citation" id=3D"some-id">
              <cite property=3D"schema:name">
                <a href=3D"http://semver.org/">Semantic Versioning 2.0.0</a=
>
              </cite>,
              by <span property=3D"schema:author" typeof=3D"schema:Person">
                <span property=3D"schema:givenName">Tom</span>
                <span property=3D"schema:familyName">Preston-Werner</span>
              </span>; published in
              <time property=3D"schema:datePublished" datatype=3D"xsd:gYear=
" datetime=3D"2014">2014</time>
              <span property=3D"schema:potentialAction" typeof=3D"schema:Re=
adAction">
                <meta property=3D"schema:actionStatus" content=3D"Completed=
ActionStatus">
                (accessed on
                <time property=3D"schema:endTime" datatype=3D"xsd:date" dat=
etime=3D"2016-02-01">01 Feb 2016</time>)
              </span>.
            </li>
          </ol>
          <figcaption>
            <span property=3D"schema:name"></span>
            <span property=3D"schema:description">
              Example of a readable citation.
            </span>
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>
          The references section is simply a <code>section</code> with an a=
ppropriate heading,
          containing an <code>ol</code>. Each <code>li</code> in the list f=
ollows a regular
          structure: it has a <code>role</code> of <code>doc-biblioentry</c=
ode>, a
          <code>resource</code> being the URL identifying the cited object,=
 a <code>property</code>
          of <a href=3D"http://schema.org/citation" class=3D"onto">schema:c=
itation</a>, and <code>id</code> to make it linkable, and a
          <code>typeof</code> capturing the kind of object that is being re=
ferenced (typically
          <a href=3D"http://schema.org/ScholarlyArticle" class=3D"onto">sch=
ema:ScholarlyArticle</a>, <a href=3D"http://schema.org/Book" class=3D"onto"=
>schema:Book</a>, or <a href=3D"http://schema.org/WebPage" class=3D"onto">s=
chema:WebPage</a> but there is
          really no limit as to what may be cited).
        </p>
        <p>
          The content of the <code>li</code> can be any <a role=3D"doc-bibl=
ioref" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/scholarly-html/#ref-RDFa">RDFa</a> tha=
t
          matches the <code>typeof</code>, but some good practices should b=
e observed.
        </p>
        <p>
          The title or name of the cited object should be in a <code>cite</=
code> element. If a link
          is available, then the title should be linked. Date and time valu=
es (such as publication
          or access date) should make use of the <code>time</code> element =
(further noting that
          the <code>datatype</code> attribute can be used to express the gr=
anularity of the date as
          in the example above).
        </p>
        <p>
          While arbitrary metadata may be used, it is highly recommended to=
 stick to
          <a role=3D"doc-biblioref" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/scholarly=
-html/#ref-schema.org">schema.org</a> and the
          <a href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/scholarly-html/#scholarly-articl=
e">Scholarly Article</a> vocabularies. The reason for that is
          that, should one wish to convert from Scholarly HTML citations in=
to a specific print
          format then it will be desirable to be able to reliably extract i=
nformation from the
          citations. This could be used for instance to produce <a role=3D"=
doc-biblioref" href=3D"https://w3c.github.io/scholarly-html/#ref-CSL">CSL</=
a>
          variables (as <a href=3D"http://citationstyles.org/developers/">e=
xemplified in the CSL
          documentation</a>) and then use a CSL implementation in order to =
produce the output.
        </p>
        <p class=3D"issue">
          Should we be more constraining and define more precisely the cons=
tructs that are more
          likely to interoperate?
        </p>
        <p class=3D"issue">
          Providing a mapping to CSL would be extremely useful.
        </p>
      </section>
      <section id=3D"footnotes">
        <!-- review? -->
        <h3><span>4.9 </span>Footnotes &amp; Endnotes</h3>
        <p>
          If the document has notes, they are listed in a <code>section</co=
de> with the role of
          <code>doc-endnotes</code>. The content of that <code>section</cod=
e> is an <code>h2</code>
          title appropriate for it, followed by either a <code>ul</code> or=
 <code>ol</code>. Each
          <code>li</code> should be labeled with the role of <code>doc-endn=
ote</code>.
        </p>
      </section>
